<p>

<b>Thirteen Steps Down</b> is a 2004 novel by <ethnic_group wordnetid="107967382" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../669/19097669.xml">
British</link></ethnic_group>
 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../025/86025.xml">
crime</link> writer <writer wordnetid="110794014" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<novelist wordnetid="110363573" confidence="0.9173553029164789">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../241/312241.xml">
Ruth Rendell</link></novelist>
</writer>
. Its publication in the UK marked Rendell's 40th anniversary of being published, and all hardcover copies of the book had a special promotional notice on the cover celebrating this.</p>

<sec>
<st>
 Plot summary</st>

<p>

The novel's main <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../315/68315.xml">
protagonist</link> is Mix Cellini (which he rigidly pronounces with an "s"), a socially-maladjusted young man who works for a company that fixes exercise equipment. Mix lives in an upstairs apartment in a decaying house in <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../200/94200.xml">
Notting Hill</link></site>
, rented out to him by the elderly Gwendoline Chawcer, who lives alone below and spends all her days reading. Mix is obsessed with two things: <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../626/42626.xml">
serial killer</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../927/1930927.xml">
John Christie</link>, and a local <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../916/48916.xml">
model</link>, Nerrissa Nash. </p>
<p>

Chawcer is a recluse with no real friends, unable to let go of a vague, yet controlling notion that the doctor who attended to her dying mother so many years ago was in love with her, as she was infatuated with him.</p>

